dy Symons-Rowe\n| 8\u20133\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 2.\n| 2008\n| [[English Amateur Championship]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} Ben Hancorn\n| 9\u20137\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 3.\n| 2008\n| [[EBSA European Snooker Championships]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Craig Steadman]]\n| 7\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 4.\n| [[2018 Challenge Tour 2|2018]]\n| [[Challenge Tour 2018/2019|Challenge Tour - Event 2]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Mitchell Mann]]\n| 3\u20130\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 5.\n| [[2018 Challenge Tour 6|2018]]\n| [[Challenge Tour 2018/2019|Challenge Tour - Event 6]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} Ben Hancorn\n| 3\u20130\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|David Grace}}\n* {{official website|http://www.davidgracesnooker.co.uk/}}\n* \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100102032100/http://global-snooker.com/David-Grace.asp?tf=1 Profile on Global Snooker]\n* [http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/david-grace/ David Grace] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101227174630/http://www.global-snooker.com/gs-news-World-Games-220709.asp Global Snooker News Article]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120926223019/http://results.worldgames2009.tw/WG_Info/en/Comp.mvc/Info/BI/StartList/BIM003401 Snooker Men Draw World Games 2009]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grace, David}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Snooker players from Leeds]]\n[[Category:World Games silver medalists]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2009 World Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = David Grace\n| image         = David Grace PHC 2012-2.jpg\n| caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2012\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1985|5|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Leeds]], [[England]] \n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname      = Amazing\n| Professional  = 2008/2009, 2011\u20132018, 2019\u2013\n| High ranking  = 43 {{smaller|(August 2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|title=WORLD RANKINGS After 2017 Evergrande China Championship|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824142606/http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/|website=World Snooker|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]163,148\n| High break    = '''139''': <br> {{smaller|2011 PTC - Event 3}} \n| Century break = 52\n| Best finish   = ''Semi-finals'' {{smaller|([[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|2015 UK Championship]])}} \n| Ranking wins  =\n| Other wins    =\n| World champ   =\n| medals-expand = yes\n| medals        =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[snooker]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{GBR2}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[World Games 2009|2009 Kaohsiung]] | [[Snooker at the World Games 2009 \u2013 men's singles|Individual]] }}\n}}\n\n'''David Grace''' (born 5 May 1985) is an [[English people|English]] professional [[snooker]] player and [[painter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0396pbt|title=Meet David Grace, professional snooker player and artist.}}</ref> After being a successful junior and amateur player, notably winning the [[English Amateur Championship]] in 2005 and 2008, he became a professional in 2008, gaining his place by winning the 2008 [[EBSA European Snooker Championships|European Snooker Championships]], where he beat [[Craig Steadman]] in the final.\n\nIn 2009, Grace took part in the men's singles snooker competition at the World Games in [[Kaohsiung]], finishing as the runner-up in this event, winning the silver medal. He entered the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|2015 UK Championship]] as the world number 81, but progressed through to his first ranking event semi-final which he lost 6\u20134 to [[Liang Wenbo]]. Grace fell off the tour in 2018, but regained his place on the tour in 2019 after finishing in the top two on the [[Challenge Tour 2018/2019]] ranking list. This earned him a two year card for the 2019/2020 and 2020/2021 seasons.\n\n==Career==\n===2011/2012 season===\nAs a new player on the tour Grace would need to win four qualifying matches in order to reach the main draw of the ranking events. He failed to win more than one match in each of his first six attempts to do this until he played in the qualifying for the [[2012 China Open (snooker)|China Open]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=67&season=2011 | title=David Grace 2011/2012 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> There he beat [[Daniel Wells (snooker player)|Daniel Wells]], [[Barry Pinches]] and [[Matthew Selt]], before losing 4\u20135 to [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] in the final round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=302 | title=2012 China Open Results | publisher=Snooker Database | accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nGrace played in all 12 of the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|Players Tour Championship]] events throughout the season, with his best finishes coming in [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 10|Event 10]] and [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 12|Event 12]], where he reached the last 16. He was ranked 63rd in the PTC [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]].<ref name=\"PTCOOM\">{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=WWW Snooker|date=8 January 2012|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref> Grace ended the season ranked world number 77 and would ordinarily be relegated from the snooker tour as he did not finish in the top 64 who retain their places.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69tDLWozD?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0%2C%2C13165~176157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=13 August 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> However, due to his performances in the PTC events, he earned his place for the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/2013 season]].<ref name=\"PTCOOM\" />\n\n===2012/2013 season===\nGrace reached the final round of qualifying for the [[2012 Shanghai Masters]] after seeing off Michael Leslie, [[Li Yan (snooker player)|Li Yan]] and [[Xiao Guodong]], but was edged out 4\u20135 by former world champion [[Peter Ebdon]] just one match away from reaching the main stage of a ranking event for the first time.<ref name=\"DG 2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=67&season=2012 | title=David Grace 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> He played in all ten [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] events this season, where he enjoyed his best result in the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|PTC Event 1]] by beating James Gillespie, [[Jimmy White]] and Gareth Allen, before losing to [[Jack Lisowski]].<ref name=\"DG 2012/13\" /> Grace was placed 74th on the PTC Order of Merit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Issued after Munich Open 2013 (ET6) |date=7 January 2013 |work=World Snooker |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/7a/ba/0,,13165~178810,00.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=27 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127034421/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/7a/ba/0%2C%2C13165~178810%2C00.pdf |archivedate=27 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> His season ended when he was beaten 9\u201310 by [[Craig Steadman]] in the first round of [[2013 World Snooker Championship#Qualifying|World Championship Qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=225 | title=Betfair World Championship Qualifiers | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> Grace fell 11 places in the rankings during the year to finish it world number 88.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0,,13165~179273,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List For The 2013/2014 Season |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=24 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611202605/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0%2C%2C13165~179273%2C00.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014 season===\nGrace went one better than last season in the qualifying rounds of the [[2013 Shanghai Masters]] by winning four matches, concluding with a 5\u20132 victory over [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]], to reach the main stage of a ranking event for the first time in his career where he was whitewashed 5\u20130 by [[Barry Hawkins]].<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=David Grace 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=67|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref> He lost his first match in all eight remaining ranking events after this.<ref name=\"2013/14\" /> Grace also had his best form in the early part of the season in the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014|European Tour]] events by reaching the last 16 of the second event, the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 2|Rotterdam Open]], where he was beaten 4\u20131 by [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]].<ref name=\"2013/14\" /> This helped him to finish 53rd on the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014#European Tour|Order of Merit]], which saw Grace earn a fresh two-year place on the tour for the [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015]] and [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/2016]] seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=European Order of Merit 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2013|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015 season===\nAt the minor-ranking [[Asian Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 1|Yixing Open]], Grace won three matches to reach the last 16 where he was whitewashed 4\u20130 by [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]].<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=David Grace 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=67|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> Grace qualified for the first ranking event of the [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015 season]], the [[2014 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] by beating [[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]] 5\u20134, but he lost 5\u20131 to [[Judd Trump]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/318357.html | title=Trump, Higgins and Robertson through at Wuxi | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> This last 64 appearance proved to be his best result in a ranking event this year.<ref name=\"2014/15\" />\n\n===2015/2016 season===\nIn the qualifying rounds for the [[2015 Shanghai Masters]], Grace beat Joe O'Connor 5\u20133, [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] 5\u20132 and [[Cao Yupeng]] 5\u20134 to reach the final round. He faced [[Ali Carter]] and defeated him 5\u20133, a victory he described as the best of his career afterwards. Grace was due to play [[Mark Selby]] in the first round, but he received a bye after Selby withdrew due to family bereavement.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/good-grace/ | title=Good Grace | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Grace\">{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/new-confidence-is-saving-grace/ | title=New Confidence is Saving Grace | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-withdraws-due-to-family-bereavement/ | title=Selby Withdraws Due to Family Bereavement | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> In the second round Grace was knocked out 5\u20131 by [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]].<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=67&season=2015 | title=David Grace 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> At the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], Grace defeated [[Andrew Higginson]] 6\u20131, [[Robert Milkins]] 6\u20132, Jack Lisowski 6\u20134 and [[Peter Ebdon]] 6\u20132 to reach the quarter-finals of a ranking event for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/uk-championship/2015-2016/david-grace-ousts-peter-ebdon-in-york-to-earn-life-changing-windfall_sto5012747/story.shtml | title=David Grace ousts Peter Ebdon in York to earn life-changing windfall | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> He fell 5\u20131 down to [[Martin Gould]], but remarkably won five successive frames to eliminate him 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/snooker/amazing-grace-stuns-gould-to-reach-uk-semi-finals-1-7608519 | title=Amazing Grace stuns Gould to reach UK semi-finals | newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> In the semi-finals, Grace built a 4\u20132 advantage over [[Liang Wenbo]], but saw it erased to be 5\u20134 behind. He then missed a simple pink in the next frame which would have taken the match to a decider, stating afterwards that he had twitched on it. Despite this, Grace earned \u00a330,000 for his first last four showing after he had made \u00a313,000 in the previous two seasons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3347748/David-Grace-misses-UK-Championship-final-Liang-Wenbo-loss.html | title=David Grace misses out on UK Championship final after Liang Wenbo loss | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> His form continued into the [[European Tour 2015/2016 \u2013 Event 5|Gibraltar Open]] where he won four matches to meet Liang in the quarter-finals and was beaten 4\u20131.<ref name=\"2015/16\" /> However, Grace could only win two out of nine matches during the rest of the season which included making his debut at the [[2016 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]] (lost 4\u20132 to [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] in the first round).<ref name=\"2015/16\" /> Grace finished a season inside the top 64 in the world rankings for the first time as he was 60th.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?cutoff=1&season=2016&template=25 | title=Historic Seedings After 2016 World Championship | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017 season===\nAt the [[2016 Paul Hunter Classic|Paul Hunter Classic]], Grace beat [[Sean O'Sullivan (snooker player)|Sean O'Sullivan]] 4\u20130 and [[Matthew Stevens]] 4\u20133 and then did not drop a frame in eliminating Jack Lisowski and [[Robbie Williams (snooker player)|Robbie Williams]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=67&season=2016 | title=David Grace 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> This saw him play in his second career ranking event quarter-final in which he led [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] 3\u20131, but lost 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web |title=Thepchaiya Un-Nooh 4\u20133 David Grace |url=http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Matches/Result/13904/451395 |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=4 October 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6l0dM7PZk?url=http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Matches/Result/13904/451395 |archivedate=4 October 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Grace was beaten 4\u20131 by [[Barry Hawkins]] in the third round of the [[2016 English Open (snooker)|English Open]] and lost in the quarter-finals of the [[2017 Snooker Shoot-Out|Shoot-Out]] to [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]].<ref name=\"2016/17\"/>\n\nGrace then qualified for his first [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] by overcoming [[Thor Chuan Leong]] 10\u20136, [[Mark Joyce]] 10\u20136 and [[Akani Songsermsawad]] 10\u20133 and played [[Kyren Wilson]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/yan-secures-crucible-debut/|title=Yan Secures Crucible Debut|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Grace only trailed 5\u20134 at the end of the first session after being 5\u20131 down and then made a century to be 7\u20136 behind. However, Wilson then took three successive frames to win 10\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/warrior-strong-grace/|title=Warrior Too Strong for Grace|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=16 April 2017}}</ref> His end-of-year ranking of 44 is the highest Grace has ever been.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings 2016/2017|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2016&template=31|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017/18 season===\nHe dropped off the tour at the end of the 2017/18 season but entered [[Q School (snooker)|Q School]] in an attempt to win back a place. <ref>http://www.worldsnooker.com/grace-remains-course-tour-return/</ref> However, his bid to regain professional status ended unsuccessfully, as he lost in all three 2018 q school events. <ref>http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Matches/Result/14018/609847/q-school-2018-event-3</ref><ref>http://www.worldsnooker.com/page-keeps-q-school-hopes-alive/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGrace also works at the Northern Snooker Centre and sells his own portrait paintings of snooker players to make extra money.<ref name=\"Grace\" />\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br/>11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br/>12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br/>18]]\n! [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/<br/>19]]\n! [[Snooker season 2019/2020|2019/<br/>20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"PTC\">Players qualified through Players Tour Championship Order of Merit started the season without ranking points.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | [[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|88]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"ET\">Players qualified through European Tour Order of Merit started the season without prize money ranking points.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | [[Snooker world rankings 2015/2016|111]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Snooker world rankings 2016/2017|60]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|44]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | <ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Riga Masters (snooker)|Riga Masters]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event was called the Riga Open (2014/2015\u20132015/2016)</ref>\n| align=\"center\" colspan=\"5\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\" | Tournament N